    <details>
      <summary>6<sup>th</sup> COMPLAINT JAUNDICE</summary>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>S: Site (Location of jaundice)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Typically observed in the skin and sclera (whites of the eyes).</li>
            <li>In severe cases, it can affect the entire body, including mucous
              membranes (e.g., inside the mouth).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>O: Onset (Rapid or chronic)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Sudden (acute) onset may suggest:
              <ul>
                <li>Acute liver injury (e.g., viral hepatitis).</li>
                <li>Bile duct obstruction (e.g., gallstones).</li>
                <li>Hemolysis (e.g., hemolytic anemia).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Gradual (chronic) onset may indicate:
              <ul>
                <li>Chronic liver disease (e.g., cirrhosis).</li>
                <li>Slow-growing obstructions (e.g., tumors).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>D: Duration (How long the jaundice has been present)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Acute: Less than 6 weeks, often linked to:
              <ul>
                <li>Infections (e.g., viral hepatitis).</li>
                <li>Acute obstructions (e.g., gallstones).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Chronic: More than 6 weeks, typically associated with:
              <ul>
                <li>Chronic liver diseases (e.g., cirrhosis).</li>
                <li>Persistent obstructions (e.g., bile duct strictures).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>A: Aggravating factors (What makes the jaundice worse)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Alcohol consumption (e.g., in alcoholic liver disease).</li>
            <li>Fatty meals (e.g., in gallstone disease, triggering biliary
              colic or obstruction).</li>
            <li>Certain medications (e.g., paracetamol, antibiotics in
              drug-induced liver injury).</li>
            <li>Infections or inflammation (e.g., worsening viral hepatitis or
              cholangitis).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>A: Associated symptoms (Other symptoms accompanying the
            jaundice)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Abdominal pain (e.g., in gallstones, pancreatitis).</li>
            <li>Fever (e.g., in infections like hepatitis, cholangitis).</li>
            <li>Weight loss (e.g., in malignancies like pancreatic or liver
              cancer).</li>
            <li>Dark urine and pale stools (e.g., in obstructive jaundice).</li>
            <li>Itching (pruritus, common in cholestatic conditions).</li>
            <li>Nausea and vomiting.</li>
            <li>Fatigue or weakness.</li>
            <li>Loss of appetite.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>C: Character/Type (Description of the jaundice)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Unconjugated (pre-hepatic):
              <ul>
                <li>Often due to hemolysis (e.g., hemolytic anemia).</li>
                <li>Genetic disorders (e.g., Gilbert&rsquo;s syndrome).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Conjugated (hepatic or post-hepatic):
              <ul>
                <li>Due to liver dysfunction (e.g., cirrhosis, hepatitis).</li>
                <li>Bile duct obstruction (e.g., gallstones, tumors).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>R: Radiation (What improves the jaundice)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Treatment of underlying cause:
              <ul>
                <li>Antivirals (e.g., for hepatitis).</li>
                <li>Surgery (e.g., for gallstones).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Avoiding alcohol or offending medications.</li>
            <li>Supportive care (e.g., hydration, nutrition).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>P: Progression (How the jaundice has changed)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Worsening, improving, or remaining stable in intensity or
              spread.</li>
            <li>Changes in associated symptoms (e.g., increasing pain or
              itching).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>P: Pattern (Characteristics of jaundice)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Constant (persistent yellowing, e.g., in chronic liver disease).</li>
            <li>Intermittent (e.g., in Gilbert&rsquo;s syndrome or intermittent
              obstructions).</li>
            <li>Associated with other symptoms (e.g., pain, fever) or isolated.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>E: Effect on life (Impact on daily activities and quality of
            life)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Fatigue or weakness affecting work or daily tasks.</li>
            <li>Social or emotional distress due to visible yellowing of skin or
              eyes.</li>
            <li>Sleep disturbances due to itching or abdominal pain.</li>
            <li>Reduced quality of life from associated symptoms like nausea or
              loss of appetite.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>R: Reserved for future expansions</strong></li>
        <li><strong>S: Scale of zero to 10 (Severity of jaundice or associated
            symptoms)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Rate the intensity of jaundice (e.g., degree of yellowing) or
              the impact of associated symptoms (e.g., pain, itching) on a scale
              from 0 (no symptoms) to 10 (severe symptoms).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </details>
