          <li><em>frequency</em></li>
          <li><em>Nocturia</em></li>
          <li><em>Hestiancy</em></li>
          <li><em>Urgency</em></li>
          <li><em>Hematuria</em></li>
          <li><br>
          </li>
          <li><strong>BPH(<b>specific</b>)</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Frequency</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Nocturia</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Urgency</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Hesitancy</strong></li>
          <li><b>Incontinence</b></li>
          <li><b>Dribbling</b></li>
          <li><strong>Hematuria</strong></li>
        </ol>
        <br>
        <ol>
          <em>
            <li>STI</li>
          </em>
          <li>ask sexual history see </li>
          <a href="Sexual%20History%20section%20CASE%20SHEET.html">Sexual
            History</a>
        </ol>
      </ol>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>P</strong>: <strong>Progression</strong> (How it&rsquo;s
          changed)</li>
        <li><b>P: </b>pattern</li>
        <ol>
          <li>Continous</li>
          <li>Intermittent<b><br>
            </b></li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>R</strong>: <strong>R</strong>ed flags</li>
        <ol>
          <li>Ca. Prostate</li>
          <li>Wt loss</li>
          <li>Tiredness</li>
          <li>Back pain</li>
          <li>lumps and bumps - nodes</li>
          <li>.</li>
          <li>Pyelonephritis</li>
          <li>Fever </li>
          <ol>
            <li>chills and rigors</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>E</strong>: <strong>Effect on life</strong> </li>
        <li><b>S: scale </b>of zero to 10</li>
      </ol>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>COMPLAINT: ERECTILE DYSFUNCTION (ED)</summary>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>NATURE OF ERECTILE PROBLEM:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Difficulty achieving an erection?</li>
            <li>Difficulty maintaining an erection until completion of sexual
              activity?</li>
            <li>Reduced rigidity of erections?</li>
            <li>Is it a new problem or a worsening of a pre-existing issue?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>ONSET &amp; DURATION:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>When did you first notice this problem? (Specific timeframe)</li>
            <li>Was the onset:
              <ul>
                <li>Sudden? (Often suggests psychogenic or acute vascular event)</li>
                <li>Gradual? (More typical for organic causes like vascular
                  disease, diabetes)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Has it been continuous or intermittent since onset?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>SEVERITY &amp; CONSISTENCY:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>How would you rate the severity? (e.g., mild, moderate, severe;
              or scale if appropriate)</li>
            <li>Does it happen every time you attempt sexual activity?</li>
            <li>Are erections present in some situations but not others?
              <ul>
                <li>e.g., Present with masturbation but not with a partner?</li>
                <li>Present on waking (nocturnal/morning erections)? (Absence
                  may suggest organic cause)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>ASSOCIATED SEXUAL SYMPTOMS:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Libido (Sex Drive):</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Any change in your desire for sex? (Increased, decreased,
                  absent)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Ejaculation:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Any problems with ejaculation? (Premature, delayed, absent,
                  painful)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Orgasm:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Any difficulty reaching orgasm?</li>
                <li>Is orgasm pleasurable?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Pain during intercourse (dyspareunia) for self or partner?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>PSYCHOLOGICAL &amp; RELATIONSHIP FACTORS:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Current mood? (Symptoms of depression, anxiety)</li>
            <li>Recent stressors? (Work, financial, family)</li>
            <li>Performance anxiety related to ED?</li>
            <li>Relationship status and quality?
              <ul>
                <li>Any recent changes or difficulties in the relationship?</li>
                <li>Communication with partner about the ED? Partner's reaction?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Past sexual trauma or negative experiences?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>MEDICAL HISTORY &amp; LIFESTYLE:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Past Medical History:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Cardiovascular disease (hypertension, heart attack, stroke,
                  peripheral vascular disease)</li>
                <li>Diabetes Mellitus</li>
                <li>Neurological conditions (e.g., MS, spinal cord injury,
                  Parkinson's)</li>
                <li>Endocrine disorders (e.g., thyroid problems, low
                  testosterone)</li>
                <li>Pelvic surgery or trauma (e.g., prostatectomy, pelvic
                  radiation)</li>
                <li>Peyronie's disease (penile curvature/pain)</li>
                <li>Mental health conditions (depression, anxiety disorders)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Medications:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Prescribed medications? (Antihypertensives, antidepressants,
                  antipsychotics, antiandrogens are common culprits)</li>
                <li>Over-the-counter medications or supplements?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Lifestyle Factors:</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Smoking history? (Quantity, duration)</li>
                <li>Alcohol consumption? (Quantity, frequency)</li>
                <li>Recreational drug use? (e.g., cannabis, cocaine, opiates)</li>
                <li>Level of physical activity/exercise?</li>
                <li>Diet? Obesity?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>PATIENT'S PERSPECTIVE &amp; IMPACT:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>What are your main concerns about this problem?</li>
            <li>How is it affecting you and/or your relationship?</li>
            <li>What are your expectations from treatment?</li>
            <li>Have you tried any treatments for ED before? If so, what and was
              it effective?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>RED FLAGS (Consider):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Sudden onset with neurological symptoms (e.g., saddle
              anesthesia, leg weakness - cauda equina)</li>
            <li>Symptoms suggestive of undiagnosed systemic illness (e.g.,
              significant weight loss, fatigue with diabetes symptoms)</li>
            <li>Penile pain, curvature, or nodules (Peyronie's disease)</li>
            <li>Symptoms of severe depression or suicidality.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <p></p>
    <p><br>
    </p>
