        <li><strong>Amoxicillin-Clavul</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>cholestatic hepatitis.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Nitrofurantoin</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>chronic hepatitis and autoimmune-like liver injury.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Flucloxacillin</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>cholestatic liver injury, especially in older adults.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Isoniazid</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatocellular injury; risk increases with age and alcohol use.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Rifampicin</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatocellular or </li>
          <li>cholestatic liver injury.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Pyrazinamide</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatotoxic potential.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Valproic Acid</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatocellular injury and microvesicular steatosis.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Phenytoin</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatocellular injury </li>
          <li>hypersensitivity reactions.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Carbamazepine</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>mixed-pattern liver injury.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Methotrexate</strong> &ndash; Long-term </li>
        <ol>
          <li>fibrosis and cirrhosis.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Amiodarone</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>chronic liver injury and steatosis.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Chlorpromazine</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>cholestatic hepatitis.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Oral Contraceptives (Estrogens)</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>cholestasis </li>
          <li>hepatocellular adenomas.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Azathioprine</strong> &ndash;</li>
        <ol>
          <li>hepatocellular or </li>
          <li>cholestatic injury.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Infliximab</strong> &ndash; hepatocellular injury.</li>
        <li><strong>Ketoconazole</strong> &ndash; hepatotoxic potential.</li>
        <li><strong>Trimethoprim-Sulfamethoxazole</strong> &ndash; </li>
        <ol>
          <li>cholestatic or </li>
          <li>mixed-pattern liver injury.</li>
        </ol>
        <li><strong>Erythromycin</strong> &ndash; cholestatic hepatitis.</li>
        <li><strong>Statins (e.g., Atorvastatin, Simvastatin)</strong> &ndash;
          Rarely cause liver injury; monitor liver enzymes.</li>
        <li>
