    <details>
      <summary>Allergy History (GIT)</summary>
      <ol>
        <li> <strong>Allergens </strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Food :</strong> Inquire about specific, diagnosed
              allergies (e.g., </li>
            <ul>
              <li>cow's milk, </li>
              <li>soy, </li>
              <li>eggs, </li>
              <li>wheat, </li>
              <li>peanuts, </li>
              <li>tree nuts, </li>
              <li>fish, </li>
              <li>shellfish).</li>
              <li> <strong>Medication&nbsp;</strong> </li>
              <li>antibiotics, </li>
              <li>NSAIDs</li>
              <li><em>DD true </em>allergic reaction <b><u>from </u></b>a
                known <b><u>side </u><u>effect </u></b>like gastritis or
                diarrhea.</li>
            </ul>
            <li><strong>Nature of GI Sx:</strong> What specific gut symptoms
              occur? (e.g., abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, cramping,
              diarrhea, bloating).</li>
            <li><strong>Timing of </strong><strong><strong>Sx</strong>:</strong>
              Are reactions </li>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>immediate</strong> (within minutes to 2 hours -
                IgE-mediated) or </li>
              <li><strong>delayed</strong> (hours to days later -
                non-IgE-mediated)?</li>
            </ul>
            <li><strong>Systemic </strong><strong><strong>Sx</strong>:</strong>
              Do other symptoms accompany the GI issues? (e.g., skin reactions
              like hives/eczema; respiratory issues like wheezing; oral
              itching/swelling).</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>Conditions </strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong><em>Eosinophilic </em>Esophagitis (EoE):</strong> A
              primary allergic condition. Ask about difficulty swallowing
              (dysphagia), food getting stuck (impaction), chest pain, and
              vomiting. A personal/family history of atopy (asthma, eczema, hay
              fever) is a major risk factor.</li>
            <li><strong>Food Protein-Induced Enterocolitis Syndrome (FPIES):</strong>
              Ask about severe, delayed (1-4 hours) projectile vomiting,
              diarrhea, and lethargy after eating a specific food (commonly
              milk, soy, grains).</li>
            <li><strong>Oral Allergy Syndrome (OAS):</strong> Ask about
              itching/swelling of the mouth and throat after eating raw fruits,
              vegetables, or nuts, which can sometimes be associated with nausea
              or abdominal pain. This is linked to pollen allergies.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>Conditions with Allergic <b><u>Overlap </u></b>or <b><u>Mimicry</u></b></strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong><em>Inflammatory </em>Bowel Disease (IBD):</strong>
              While autoimmune, food allergies/intolerances can trigger IBD
              flares. Ask if the patient has noticed specific food triggers for
              their Crohn's or Ulcerative Colitis symptoms.</li>
            <li><strong><b><u>Irritable </u></b>Bowel Syndrome (IBS):</strong>
              Inquire if IBS symptoms (pain, bloating, altered bowel habits) are
              consistently triggered after consuming certain foods, as a food
              hypersensitivity may be a contributing factor for a subset of
              patients.</li>
            <li><strong><b>Celiac </b>Disease:</strong> It is crucial to
              differentiate this autoimmune disorder from a wheat allergy. Ask
              about a formal diagnosis. Also, inquire about symptoms of lactose
              intolerance, which can be a temporary secondary issue due to gut
              damage in untreated celiac disease.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </details>
